According to the numerical and graphical summaries and considering the dataset description provided, the following things can be concluded:

  1. large_family: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.67 gives us the proportion that 67% of male students or majority of the male students have a family size greater than 3 people.
  2. lives_in_city: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.76 gives us the proportion that 76% of male students or majority of male students live in urban areas.
  3. traveltime: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 1 to 4. The mean of 1.49 suggests that, on average, male students have a travel time of less than 15 minutes and the distribution is right skewed as clear from the histogram.
  4. studytime: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 1 to 4. The mean of 1.76 indicates that, on average, male students spend less than 2 hours per week studying. In this case as well the distribution is right skewed.
  5. failures: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 0 to 3 denoting number of classes failed in the past. The mean of 0.37 indicates that, on average, male students have less than one(or zero) past class failure. In this case as well the distribution is right skewed.
  6. paid: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.39 suggests that around 39% of male students take extra paid classes.
  7. activities: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.56 suggests that around 56% of male students or majority of male students participate in extra-curricular activities.
  8. internet: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.85 indicates that around 85% of male students or majority of the male students have internet access at home.
  9. romantic: It is a binary indicator. The mean of 0.28 suggests that around 28% of male students are in a romantic relationship.
  10. famrel: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 1 (very bad) to 5 (excellent). The mean of 4.00 indicates that, on average, male students have a good relationship with their family. In this case the distribution is left skewed.
  11. freetime: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 1 (very low) to 5 (very high). The mean of 3.49 suggests a moderate distribution of free time among male students. Its clear from the histogram that there is slight skewness in the negative direction or left skewed distribution.
  12. goout: It is a numeric indicator with categories ranging from 1 (very low) to 5 (very high). The mean of 3.20 indicates male students have a moderate level of going out with friends.Since the distribution doesn't give much hint about the skewness, we will use the skewness coefficient which is approx 0.09 which indicates that the distribution is slightly right skewed.
  13. absences: It is a numeric indicator with values ranging from 0 to 93. The mean of 5.14 suggests a male student on an average is absent for 5 days.
  14. final_grade: It is a numeric indicator with values ranging from 0 to 20. The mean of 10.91 indicates an average final grade of approximately 10.91 out of 20.The distribution according to the histogram looks approximately normal but the values nearby zero are making it left skewed and this fact is backed by the skewness coefficient of approximately -0.76. Therefore the distribution is left skewed.

Note: This method can only be used if the two datasets have equal number of columns.Furthermore, if the order of columns in both the datasets is same then and then only we will get all elements of the boolean array as False according to the specified condition.

A better and more generalised method for checking whether two datasets have same columns or not is illustrated in the following defined function.

In [15]:
def are_datasets_alike(df1,df2):
    #checking if datasets have equal number of columns
    if df1.shape[1]!=df2.shape[1]:
        return False
    
    for i in df1.columns:
        #if a column of df1 is not found in df2 return False
        if i not in df2.columns:
            return False
    #full execution of loop means df1 and df2 have identical columns
    return True

are_datasets_alike(male_stud_df,female_stud_df)
Out[15]:
True

The result for whether the datasets are alike is True as expected.

We need to find the largest 4 values excluding ones from this dataframe. Lets define a function for the same which will input the correlation matrix and a number n and return the n pairs of feature names in the form of tuple which are highly correlated alongwith their correlation coefficient.

In [20]:
def findMaxCorrelatedFeatures(corr_mat,n):
    out=[]
    corr_mat=corr_mat[corr_mat!=1] #remove all the entries of self correlation
    #At each iteration of while loop the max correlated pair's information will be appended to the output list
    while n>0:
        max_val=float('-inf')
        temp=[None]*3
        #final max correlation value to be appended to output will be generated after the for loop
        for i in corr_mat.columns:
            #finding the position of max_correlation in series
            max_correlated_feature_index=corr_mat[i].abs().argmax()
            
            currentMax=abs(corr_mat[i][max_correlated_feature_index])
            if currentMax>max_val:
                max_val=currentMax
                temp[0]=i#column index
                temp[1]=corr_mat.columns[max_correlated_feature_index]#row index
                temp[2]=corr_mat[i][max_correlated_feature_index]#correlation coefficient
        
        out.append((temp[0],temp[1],temp[2]))#appending the final values in the output array
        
        #resetting the values in the correlation_matrix to zero for pairs added to output
        #this is being done to ensure that values already added to output are not considered in the next
        #iteration
        corr_mat.loc[temp[0],temp[1]]=corr_mat.loc[temp[1],temp[0]]=0
        n-=1
        
    return out

max_correlated_features=findMaxCorrelatedFeatures(correlation_matrix,4)

We had justified above that there is weak correlation according to correlation coefficients which can also be seen in the above scatterplots.

  • In the first plot between final grade and number of failures, it is clear that all students in different categories of failures have a straight line relationship(constant:neither increasing nor decreasing,slope = 0) with final grade.
  • In the second plot between travel time and lives in city, it is clear that travel time of students is having a straight line relationship irrespective of the fact whether a student lives in city or not.
  • In the third plot between go out and free time, it is clear that students belonging to each category of free time have a straight line relationship with each category of go out. In other words, freetime is not highly correlated with going out as each of its category has evenly distributed students from all categories of go out. In layman terms,a student who doesn't have much free time may have any frequency of going out and the converse a student who has a greater level of free time may have any frequency of going out, both are true.
  • In the fourth plot between internet and lives in city, it is clear that students belonging to each category of internet have a straight line relationship with each category of lives in city. In other words, a student who lives in city may or may not have internet and the converse i.e a student who doesn't live in city may or may not have internet, both are true.

D¶

Defining a function for forward selection of predictors using AIC as the criteria.
The function defined below takes in 2 parameters:

  1. The predictors dataframe with intercept column added
  2. The series of response data.
    This function outputs a list of positions corresponding to best predictors selected in the transformed dataframe passed i.e. predictors dataframe with intercept columns.
    Note: The list of positions returned includes the position of intercept column as well at the 0th index.
In [28]:
def forwardAIC(covariates,response):
    #will only work if the intercept term is already present at the first position in covariates dataframe
    ind=0
    column_indexes=[ind]#index of intercept, for initialization step of null model
    # this flag will indicate whether a subset of covariates that decreases AIC is found
    # if true,the loop continues to run and checks for further subsets that decrease AIC
    # if at any point in time the AIC is not reducing further then the loop ends
    
    flag=True #initializing as True for the first run of while loop
    
    while(flag):#loop terminated when flag is false
        maxDecreaseAIC=float('-inf')
        flag=False #toggled to false
        curr_mod = sm.Logit(response,covariates.iloc[:,column_indexes])
        curr_res = curr_mod.fit(disp=0)# silencing "Optimization Termination" output using "disp" param

        for j in range(covariates.shape[1]):
            if (j not in column_indexes):
                new_mod=sm.Logit(response,covariates.iloc[:,column_indexes + [j]])
                new_res=new_mod.fit(disp=0)
                difference_aic=curr_res.aic-new_res.aic
                if (difference_aic > 0 and difference_aic>maxDecreaseAIC):
                    maxDecreaseAIC=difference_aic
                    ind=j
                    flag=True
        if (flag):#if true append the column index
            column_indexes.append(ind)
            
    return column_indexes#includes the intercept
    
        
selected_cols=forwardAIC(predictors_with_intercept,response)

D¶

In [35]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

# defining the list of tree
num_trees_list = [5, 10, 50, 100, 500, 1000, 5000]
n = len(num_trees_list)

# Initialize zero arrays with size n for storing means of r_squared and its standard error
mean_r_squared = np.zeros(n)
std_r_squared = np.zeros(n)

# Loop over different numbers of trees
for i, num_trees_value in enumerate(num_trees_list):
    
    # Initialize zero to store r_squared for each iteration
    r_squared_values = np.zeros(20)

    # Repeat the model fitting and prediction
    for j in range(20):  # fit the model 20 times and store r_squared_value
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=num_trees_value, random_state=j*2)

        # Fit the model to the training data
        model.fit(xTrain, yTrain)

        # Make predictions on the test set
        yPred = model.predict(xTest)

        # Calculate R-squared value
        r_squared_values[j] = r2_score(yTest, yPred)

    mean_r_squared[i] = np.mean(r_squared_values)
    std_r_squared[i] = np.std(r_squared_values)

# Plot the results
plt.errorbar(num_trees_list, mean_r_squared, yerr=std_r_squared, fmt='o-', capsize=5)
plt.xscale('log')  # Log scale for the number of trees
plt.xticks(num_trees_list, [str(num) for num in num_trees_list])#change the ticks to represent actual number of trees
plt.xlabel('Number of Trees')
plt.ylabel('Mean R-squared (with Standard Error)')
plt.title('Random Forest Regression Performance vs. Number of Trees')
plt.show()

Its clear from the plot between model performance and number of trees ,that as the number of trees are increasing the mean of r_squared values is increasing alongwith a decrease in standard error for means of r_squared values. Another important thing to notice here is that the standard error as well as the r_squared values remains constant starting from 500 trees.

E¶

Fitting the model multiple times with different random states is essentialy useful if we wanna test the robustness and generalizability of model. Also, the rationale for doing so lies in the fact that due to randomness in selecting features at each split in this technique ,some amount of variability is introduced in the model. Therefore, fitting the model multiple times can help in providing insights into the stability and robustness of the model across different initializations.

Question 6¶

A¶

Now. Lets try to cluster datapoints using a widely used technique called K-Means Clustering.

In [36]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

k=list(range(1,11))
silhoutte_score_list=[]
#this is the sum of squared distances of each datapoint from the center of their respective clusters.
euclidean_dist_sum=[]

for i in k:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=i,random_state=101)
    model.fit(combined_df)
    euclidean_dist_sum.append(model.inertia_)# inertia represents total sum of squared distances
    
    if i!=1:#silhoutte_score is not defined on a single cluster
        silhoutte_score_list.append(silhouette_score(combined_df, model.labels_))

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.plot(k,euclidean_dist_sum,'cx-',)
plt.title("Line plot of number of clusters(k) vs total inertia")
plt.ylabel("Total Inertia")
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters(k)")
plt.xticks(k)
plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.plot(k[1:],silhoutte_score_list,'rx-',)
plt.title("Line plot of number of clusters(k) vs Silhoutte Score")
plt.ylabel("Average Silhoutte Score")
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters(k)")
plt.xticks(k)
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)#Adjusting the vertical distance between subplots
plt.show()

We have used Elbow method first to get some understanding of the optimal value of k. In this method we plot inertias for models against different values of k and see the point after which there is not a significant decrease in inertia values. The line plot around ideal candidates of k would have an elbow like formation.

As can be seen from the plot,the inertia for the model dropped suddenly (elbow like formation) for values of k in the range [4-6] and is not dropping much post k=6. Therefore the potential candidates for optimal k are: 4, 5, 6

The second approach that we used to enforce our claim about range of optimal k was Average Silhoutte Score analysis for different values of k and and filter out a value of k from the range of k found earlier by analysing inertia values which gives the maximum Average Silhoutte Score.

Silhoutte score gives a measure of how similar a datapoint is within a cluster compared to other clusters or its compactness . The values of Silhoutte score range from -1 to 1 where, a score of 1 denotes that the datapoint is compact and close to the centroid of the cluster and far away from other clusters, and a score of -1 is worst which depicts that the clusters are overlapping.

From the plot between number of clusters(k) Vs average Silhoutte score, it is clear that k=4 is the optimal number of clusters for this data following the approach explained above.

D¶

We will be using HDBSCAN (Hierarchical Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) for clustering the data. This techique can discover clusters of varying shapes and densities and it doesn't require us to specify the number of clusters that we want to create beforehand. Rather, it asks for min_cluster_size as input which specifies the minimum number of datapoints which need to be grouped together in order to form a cluster.

Since, we cannot specify number of clusters we want to construct we will simply fit the model using values of min_cluster_size over a range and see which one fits the model best.

Note: We can only test the models effectiveness using Silhoutte score as HDBscan considers density of points for selecting clusters rather than minimising the sum of squared distances from centroid.

In [41]:
# importing library for HDBSCAN
from sklearn.cluster import HDBSCAN
# k: number of clusters not applicable
min_cluster_size_list=list(range(2,21))

silhoutte_score_list=[]
                        
for i in min_cluster_size_list:
    model = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=i)
    model.fit(combined_df)
    silhoutte_score_list.append(silhouette_score(combined_df, model.labels_))


plt.plot(min_cluster_size_list,silhoutte_score_list,'rx-',)
plt.title("Line plot of Minimum Cluster Size vs Average Silhoutte Score")
plt.ylabel("Average Silhoutte Score")
plt.xlabel("Minimum Cluster Size(n)")
plt.xticks(min_cluster_size_list)
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)#Adjusting the vertical distance between subplots
plt.show()

Its clear from the above plot that Silhoutte score suffers a sharp increase as min_cluster_size jumps from 2 to 3 and remains approximately constant after that.

The Silhoutte score in context of HDBScan has different interpretation which is listed below : -

  • A score near 1 suggests that datapoint within a cluster are far away from other clusters.
  • A score of 0 signifies datapoint is very close to the decision boundary within a cluster.
  • A negative score indicates that the data point is closer to the neighboring cluster than to its own assigned cluster which suggests that the point might be more fitting in another cluster and its current assignment is less appropriate.
  • Note: The range of Silhoutte Score is in the range [-1,1] .

Since, the Silhoutte score seemed approximately constant after min_cluster_size = 2, we can filter out the min_cluster_size which was giving us the best model fit using the list of silhoutte score that we created earlier and use it to fit the best mode.
The implementation is shown below:

In [42]:
#computing the index in min_cluster_size_list which corresponds to max silhoutte score
optimal_min_cluster_size=min_cluster_size_list[np.array(silhoutte_score_list).argmax()]
finalmodel = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=optimal_min_cluster_size)
labels=finalmodel.fit_predict(combined_df)
labels#making predictions on data to see cluster labels

Listing down important differences of results obtained through K-Means Clustering and HDBSCAN :-

  • The approximate best Silhoutte score obtained from K-Means Clustering approach was around 0.45 whereas HDBSCAN produced the best approximate Silhoutte score of 0.4 which suggests the former approach was better in fitting the model.
  • The optimal number of clusters which were giving the best model fit in K-Means clustering was 4 whereas HDBSCAN approach was producing 3 clusters.
  • In the K-Means clustering approach 5 variables emerged as most discriminatory variables whereas in HDBSCAN approach 3 variables emerged as most discriminatory. Furthermore, the most discriminatory variables emerged in the K-Means clustering approach had 2 extra variables namely freetime and studytime in comparison to most discriminatory variables found using the HDBSCAN approach.
